The Ukrainian parliament today declined the request to abolish the paragraph on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko was convicted in a Criminal Code amendment.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned former Prime Minister, the deputies rejected at the second reading of the request to mitigate the penalties for economic crimes.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for the conclusion of an allegedly adverse agreement with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not yet enforceable, and the appeal of the convicted will be tried in court in December.
Timoshenko himself describes the judgment as a political revenge of the regime and also in the West the trial caused suspicion of the court’s prejudice.
The request, paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Prime Minister was convicted, to remove from the Criminal Code was supported by 147 MPs.
226 votes would have been required for its adoption.
