The menu of a fat-addicted child: it does not have breakfast and eat sausage for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, with 9 percent of all pupils and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important the environment in which he grows up is for the healthy development of a person and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more common on the table than in families where children with normal weight live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had dinner potatoes the day before the enlightenment campaign under the motto “Obesity is not a coincidence.”
In families with thickers, sport is not one of the favorite activities, but the majority of today’s students – only 15 percent responded that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year at the end of the school year, with nearly 900 children from primary schools in the Czech Republic being surveyed.
This was already the second year of the action "Obesity is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Insurance and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th classes participated in the project.
Unhealthy eating and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the terrifyingly increasing number of children with overweight or even obesity.
“Only half of the children surveyed, for example, suggested eating breakfast-lunch-second breakfast-vesper evening bread five times a day – one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet,” one of the survey results said.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that also relative little things, such as the family’s regular breakfast time, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the students’ families eat breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
The worst was the finding that in every tenth family there is no breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the foundation of a healthy daily diet.
The survey test revealed, among other things, that in families of overweight children, unhealthy potatoes are consumed much more often.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonade every day (70%)
Although more than 40 percent of children surveyed do sports, less than half of their parents do so – that is, only 15 percent.
Create your own menu
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compile their own dining schedule from the options offered by appetite and opinion.
“What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favorite dishes were many flour dishes, meat dishes and, of course, sweets.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet lemonades," the final report on this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, i.e. the main dish, dough beat shortly before poultry.
Legumes the children almost did not like and also the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to Health
At the same time, the survey also showed that the children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get proper information.
"In the control group of respondents who completed the questionnaire after the enlightening lecture "Obesity is not a coincidence", there was a significant shift in preferences towards healthy eating principles in many cases," the results of the project stated.
This was eye-catching, for example, with the sweet limes, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
The children also crossed in the questionnaire much more often poultry or fish as the main dish of the day and were willing to eat fewer knobs or sweet foods.
