V Need for Speed: "The Run" - The Illegal Race across America
Reviews
The originally careless ride is made by a series of completely avoidable, dilettant errors to the routine ride to the early class.
It was possible to fulfill the ambitions to a large extent, but what’s the benefit of it when no one obviously wanted to do a little more.
Even before it came to the store tables, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" awakened high expectations.
He promised to move the old-fashioned game series "Need for Speed" back to a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples it didn't seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about the fitted passages in which the main protagonist climbs out of the car and goes on foot.
But as you’re already used to NFS, in the end, it’s much different than you expected.
Sure - potentially it's fairly decent arcade races, but overall the game is diminished by some superfluous mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So they are actually no longer mistakes, but rather signs of a laziness in principle of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time you are introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has some personal problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the west coast, you sit on the steering wheel with the task of being the first to be in New York.
The basic idea includes a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race will be held on a different track and that the individual stages will take place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You don’t have the impression that the game would offer the same thing again and again.
Some environments are still very beautiful to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not exceed that of the previous parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the ride through the desert, through autumn landscape or high up through deeply snowy landscape seems visually very pleasant.
Sometimes untypical elements bring a bit of variation to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, you are surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts your sight.
In the mountains, in turn, you have to be careful not to be spilled by an avalanche.
On the other hand, the individual races are built up quite well in a row.
Just a few, but they're enough.
For a while you try to surpass the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you expect a personal duel with a single opponent.
The police are also involved, who want to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty is passages where Jack leaves the car.
It is more about certain interactive animations where Jack flees from anyone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
However, it is surprising that there are much fewer such passages in the game than you would expect (specifically only three).
Ultimately, this is rather an advantage of the thing, because so at least this element has no chance of getting bored - it is one of the elements that make the game more varied in the context of the above.
The driving model follows the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today’s point of view, it doesn’t tear out trees, but on the other hand it couldn’t be said to be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look around elsewhere.
But a race loaded with actions will continue to meet the local driving model quite well, although you could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in order.
Real problems arise only after a certain time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not entirely OK.
It is hard to expect from a game of this kind that it calculates complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea before any impact on any object how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is okay.
Typical example: When you overtake or pass cars that meet you "strip" the other cars in some places only slightly, but in other, almost identical situations, you get into sneaking and turn wild pirouettes.
Or the car will go straight to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn’t matter any more, but it’s always annoying.
The restarts are so resolved: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then you throw the game back to the last point of the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
When you've exhausted them, everything starts from the fore.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something fails, but you shouldn’t rely on it.
Sometimes, however, even the restart doesn’t help, because nothing else helps than learning the critical section from your head.
Extremely unpleasant is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, have to go through in a very specific way, otherwise you just don’t get through.
Somewhere else you will always meet "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you are the first or the fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see the opponent passing two cars in front of a game, but until you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
And it doesn’t matter when you get there, because everything is designed to make this situation always close to your nose.
The counterparts have other advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken at the same place by the same opponent and here again regardless of the time.
The craziest is at the end of the game on the long bridge that you pass in the opposite direction.
The counterpart must obviously overtake one here on devil come out.
And when he is before one, he of course takes the sight of you, so that you start driving your own car there a few times in Klump.
Clearly - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly misses the joy of the game.
And that’s a shame, because despite the simpler driving model, the game overall is quite entertaining and sometimes so loaded with action that you almost no longer know where one’s head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "fault" is - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boring can happen, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the car change during the race.
You should not overlook the gas stations on the track, because right here you can change the car, although in most cases the car you have just enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for urban areas, the strong American limousines for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical rides, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the game history mode also goes the task mode (challenges) - that is, the races in the individual locations that you know from the story.
Here there are not only medals, but also to gain experience points for your own profile, which is jointly for the tasks (challenges) and the history.
In order to reach the higher driver level, various items must be opened: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is simultaneously connected to the online function Autolog, which, among other things, compares its own achieved results with those of other players and also provides additional collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the last race in history.
Here you can get by car to a subway tunnel (minestly because), where you can run in the dark on the rails for a long time (minestly because).
Figures look at the tacho between 150 and 200 km/h (because of mine), but there suddenly comes a subway from behind and drives an uncompromising scrap.
In our editorial, we will probably argue for a long time whether this was a blackout of the game designer or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is quite appealing in most cases and even brilliant here and there.
The more annoying it is that at some exciting moments, the frequency of retrieval slows down, and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
This, however, applies in particular to accidents with a larger number of participants, where a continuous FPS does not benefit you anyway.
The sound is so far OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to as wide a scale as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack a-la created "from everyone something" - but who buys such a game because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game wasn’t undermined by the above-mentioned totally unnecessary errors, we could have claimed with the chest tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But this is how the game looks unfinished.
It is a great pleasure in itself, but you should be prepared to get these errors in your eyes with the power of airport headlights.
Concert of "Students of the Velvet Revolution" with singing ensembles of the Karlsuniversity
The Festival Festa Academica now offers for the third time the refinement of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution and this with music experience.
During the festival, the twenty college choirs will be presented.
The festival focuses on the two concerts that will take place on November 17.
"The Charles University has a big part in the festival."
“Among the participants, the choir of the Pedagogical Faculty and the Faculty of Humanistic Studies is also represented, and the festival committee is also represented by Rector Václav Hampl,” said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organization team.
Absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of specialized school choirs, which will take place on November 17th at 2 p.m. on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes the composition of the prominent Czech jazz artist Karel Růžička "Celebration Jazz Mass".
In the evening hours, in the Galarooms of the Volkshaus in Vinohrady, the concert "Studenten der Velzenen Revolution" (Studenty sametu) takes place, in which also university choirs perform, choirs of the Karlsuniversity do not exclude.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate World Student Day and commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but to present choir music to the public at the highest level and to promote the creative collaboration of young people.
The main organizer is the Association of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Johannes-Kepler-Gymnasium.
Bohuslav Svoboda, the mayor of the capital Prague, and Václav Hampl, the rector of the Charles University, took over the guardianship over the entire event.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
In addition to concerts, the schedule also includes numerous music meetings, student happings, matinees and other events.
Detailed information can be found on the websites of the festival www.festaacademica.cz
