IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
The company IBM (International Business Machines), founded in New York a hundred years ago, initially had a rather complicated name – Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later IBM company was the merger of four companies, whose history goes back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They owned technologies such as the famous stitch-card watches for the registration of the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company became Charles Ranlett Flint, who was also chaired by the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
This leader then even shadowed the founders of IBM - based on Watson's ideas, the company's invincible culture and identity is still based on today.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM started, as the name suggests, with the production and sale of all possible machines for retail – from sausage and cheese cutters to cashiers.
In the first four decades of Watson’s leadership, he doubled sales to nine million dollars and gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so essential to the company that he was in the chief chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM technicians and computers helped NASA to direct flights to space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also man's famous flight to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which established the computer standard of that time, was launched in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but acquired the consulting part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered into the business of consulting services and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the concept of “Smarter Planet”.
It embodies the intention to use technologies in a wise manner in areas not even planned so far, e.g. also to improve the situation in transport and city administration.
In the trading sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smart Commerce” platform, which is designed to help traders steer the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM founded a branch in the Czechoslovakia at the time – as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern Europe Headquarters is located in Prague and there is also a world-class research team dealing with voice recognition technology.
