Evolution of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorized state travel agencies in the then-CSSR: Čedok, Sportist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
The travel agencies at the time only sold travel to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, in the West only chosen people were allowed at the time.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimea peninsula by the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you were also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A major paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the CSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then the travel agencies offered travel to the west, but then you had to buy huge queues or even stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
This was not the way for a long time.
The so-called currency promise - the condition for a trip to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
Indeed, the Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to find the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a commitment to currency.
Most Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and datches - a habit that continues to this day.
The 1989 velvet revolution followed a travel revolution by the Czechs.
While until 1989 a vacation in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their vacations abroad in countries around the world.
An enormous paradox, which is no longer aware of today, is the fact that you could not travel to the most popular holiday country of the Czechs today - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
From the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange duty was lifted in neighbouring Western European countries, which led to a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn’t get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymakers slept in the tent in the park when travelling to Paris, for who would have had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a guesthouse at the time.
A typical feature of Czechs travelling abroad was then a trunk packed with canned, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech krone - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our living standards and the average wages increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies began regularly preparing charter flights after 1997, making air travel incredibly cheaper than the past thanks to the ability to negotiate quantity discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, already had currency-free payments with all the highly developed countries in the world, making traveling even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-summary" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight was made to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers fly to distant sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
The Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the era that characterized our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely ranked among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent for the first time more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history spent more than 15 TZK per capita for a single vacation stay including the cost at the resort.
