He made the architect so famous that he also built the pavilion at the next World Exhibition in Austria.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like side building in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
Its pavilion, planned as a temporary exhibition building, had been erected after the World Exhibition in the Swiss garden at the Vienna South Railway Station, rebuilt and opened a museum of the 20th century in 1962 - the "20er Haus" was called it.
But the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls to hang art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has come down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum of contemporary art.
Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition - a luck in every way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, an art historian with a remarkable career, graduated from youth as an ice skater, later at Sotheby’s, the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Museum of Modern Salzburg, focused on the transformation of politicians and monumental guardians, raising public funds and private sponsors.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there should be a cafe and a bookstore, and an office house had to be built to do so.
Strict supervision, small state
For the implementation, Krischanitz was the ideal occupation.
Not only because he rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna sensitively and won the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was a "monsterly important place" for him, where he had watched the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost generosity and ease as soon as it was moved to Vienna and reused.
There were far greater problems with the current conversion: the building was "an energy scrap", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, glass fiber reinforced insulating glass was inserted and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel carriers have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been restored.
Two basements provided space for new use, a lowered light pit between the house and the street ensures exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the lightweight dick pavilion.
The original outside doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red brown rust-proof colour.
The cinema is exactly as it was before.
And all this under the strict supervision of the Monument Authority and with a small budget.
"Often we had to find a material that is good and cheap and also liked the Office of the Monumental Protection," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and conversions, the building has remained flexible and easy.
It had been difficult with the pavilion that “comed from Brussels,” Krischanitz recently said, a typical “drop-in-the-city history.”
Such an architecture stands "always in the wrong place" and yet wants to "raise a real awareness".
