Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before he became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many boys who sent his anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to committing an attack in Norway in July in which 77 people were killed, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is by far not alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time until his attack in front of his computer and chatted with some of the millions of nationalists supporting far-right groups on social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
This is easy – you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We found that it was not difficult to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the UK’s DEMOS idea factory on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, researchers simply need to use the advertising tool of the site to exactly define their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy – just as marketers have done for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with adds, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the adds invited users to a survey that asked about their level of education, their attitude toward violence, and the assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to question more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without even once having to leave their office.
“It’s a pretty new research method,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are hardly surprising. Online supporters of far-right groups are mostly young, male and are annoyed by immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends such as "likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three contents per day, Facebook’s data supernova generates a research boom that has increased the number of research papers with the name of this page in the title by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that through this page you can study people you normally don’t reach with your clipboard on the street.
“If you tried to question people of the British National Party before, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“They had to inform the party first and it would never have granted them access,” Bartlett says.
“At Facebook, it’s all gone – you’re going straight to them.”
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their full noise on Facebook are significantly more prone to problem drinking than students who were silent about this topic.
Moreno suggests that equal-level students, such as residential consultants, monitor the site and help a student post too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem if you haven’t recognized it,” Dimitri Christakis, Moreno’s co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle told the Washington Post.
“We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who would not have been found otherwise.”
Facebook is also constantly capturing the data of its own population.
The site’s data team has created statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, election participation in the 2010 mid-elections, and a national happiness index (which primarily used information that only Facebook has access - masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its large data foundation available to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they want it or not. To be able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you allow the site to share your own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles at all,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study in which he studied the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As for her, it was about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a researcher is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information in a user profile and in posts is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
So, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research has to take care of the social – and a lot of social life is still taking place offline.”
