Climate challenges slow down the economy
In the first year of Mario López Valdez in the government, unemployment and black labour rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 is remembered in Sinaloa’s economic history. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who calls himself the initiator of change and boosting great hopes for economic growth, is at the government. However, due to climatic difficulties, growth can not be talked about, but rather deteriorated the main economic indicators.
The low temperatures in February not only caused million-high losses in agriculture, but also put tight boundaries on the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6 percent in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historic decline in agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which had a slow impact on other economic sectors.
According to a report issued by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexico’s Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582,000 hectares of agricultural land used were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has led to a continuous increase in unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, since from January to March 55 053 Sinaloa inhabitants had no employment in the first quarter, equivalent to 4.53 percent of the labour force.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment rate in Sinaloa this year is due to several factors. Economist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autonoma (UAS), comments that the policies of public institutions indirectly declare the rise in unemployment.
“What we’re currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including liquidity losses in the market as a result of the money cuts passed by legislation to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who illegally accumulate dollars, it’s not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else,” he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment also has a demographic factor inherent.
"The number of people leaving the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased. This is due on the one hand to the problems of entry and on the other because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here looking for work, which causes unemployment to rise," he says.
Black labour
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, taking into account the high proportion of black labour, which according to INEGI covers 60.38 percent of the employees in the country who work without depositing in the social security funds.
Unemployment and black labour include low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexico Social Security Institute) and the Secretaria del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Mexico’s Government of Labour and Social Care).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos until September, much less than the total government average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and rising unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years was recorded in 2011. According to the Secretariat de Economia, the ADI was $630,597 from January to June, equivalent to a loss of 87.74 percent compared to the $5,143,312 in the same period in the previous year.
The Secretaria de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Governmental Authority for Economic Development) has a total investment of 17,280,000 pesos in 2011, primarily from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
In the face of the economic crisis in July, the state government applied for a loan of 3,000,000,000,000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy. The state congress approved an amount of 200,000,000 pesos, but no positive impact of debt on any of the country's industries was found by November.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of Mario López Valdé’s rule became apparent.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of the Manufacturing Industry in Mexico) said that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonize the views of different sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year, it is necessary to work hard to recover the land lost this year and in 2012 we have to double our efforts. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López stated that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year complicated and slowed the country's economic development.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important effects is a slowed economy that is not in motion enough to generate an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. That is why we will complete the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefine vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, Chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexican Entrepreneurship Association) in Sinaloa, declared that it was necessary to encourage the state to take more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done, and we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to re-determine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There's a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that drives the government’s efforts on better track.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He stressed that the current state power has made progress in the government.
"There are areas where you can say that the government has acted more comprehensively, and what I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
