The possibility of individual counting of votes is a reality in the Michoacán elections this year, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between the first and second places in the governor elections is just about 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that only last November 9th, the electoral office had adopted a series of regulations to harmonize local regulations with state reforms in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that neither Michoacán’s political constitution, nor his electoral law, nor his electoral justice law had adapted to the reforms passed by Congress, so that they did not enter into force at this round of elections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional suit filed by the local legislature and judged the representative’s voice on the constitutional reforms as “invalid and unlawful” as he has no right to “decide or veto it.”
María de los Ángeles Llanderal stated in an interview on the possibility of individual counting of votes that thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, the local electoral authority could now count the votes in part or in full.
For example, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be counted in part under the following conditions. The results in the protocols do not agree; the protocol on the counting and calculation of votes is not present or is not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the protocols.
Furthermore, the overall counting of fully completed votes may be made if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the second-placed winner that is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman before who is the second of the said candidates.
The total counting of votes may also be made if, after the ordinary calculation has been completed, it is determined that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in the second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate has become second.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second places is almost 0.16%, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 election protocols have not yet been counted.
