Asphalt from UNAM prevents crashing holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM developed polymer-modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If attention was paid to the signs coming from the road flooring, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 bumper holes if the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the valley of Mexico) broke out, Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, warning and assuring that if the bumper was brokened,
In his lecture "Blagholes from a technical point of view", which he held on the occasion of the International Year on Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but that has a greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of road flooring and thus avoid the appearance of bumper holes.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphene - and the other part a low - the so-called malthene. Together they give the road flooring its characteristic tough elastic behavior.
Tensilelast behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of nearly 180° C., it is very tense at 120° C. and almost firm at 50° C., while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
“This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations,” said the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that Mexico City’s streets have a majority of flexible road flooring composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers there is a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer has been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows a good force distribution in the road flooring.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be distributed even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "is laid a final layer, the so-called carrier layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tyres, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they have to produce friction.
In addition, the support layer requires an appropriate thickness and the material from which it is composed must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially water," he said, "because it significantly impairs the behavior of the wear layer.
When the site becomes moist, water penetrates into the layer and is difficult to return, causing a softening of all layers of road flooring and, as a result, the appearance of bumper holes.
"If a hole arises," he said, "the cover layer will first be removed, while the wear layer will only be affected afterwards, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by adequate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexican National Research System) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of bumper holes and that the thickness of each layer of road flooring must always be proportional to the vehicle load and ensure that this regulation is complied with to avoid frequent bumper holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example about asphalt emulsions that are already on the market in other countries, and with which the drums could be repaired easily and without the application of high temperatures.
