The world chip card fair opens its doors in Villepinte near Paris in an optimistic attitude on Tuesday.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 should actually end with a 11% increase in worldwide sales of microprocessor chips (EC cards, SIM card phones), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment here is the contactless technology that enables payments in public transport or payment of purchases by simply holding the card to a reader.
Compared to the 320 million sold a year earlier, 460 million contactless chip cards are expected to be sold worldwide this year!
Its market share is expected to increase further in 2012 (580 million expected units) and represent more than 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe is gaining on the ground in terms of contactless payments after a long time behind the Asia-Pacific region.
Some 26 million Visa cards are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards were distributed.
However, consumer markets are steaming.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCards this year.
In order to move to a higher speed, it is now necessary for banks to equip their customers with these cards.
“Two major French financial institutions have committed to systematically handing over to their customers bank cards equipped with contactless chip in the future,” said Gérard Nébouy, General Director of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by cell phone
However, this is only a first step on the way to the payment method of the future: the mobile phone.
A disappearingly small percentage of devices have so far been equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology necessary to carry out these transactions.
"They've been late."
"But they should at least experience a real upward development next year."
“We expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012,” said Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
The banks are taking initiative.
Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees are expected to be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
BPCE is running a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And Société Générale also testified yesterday to prepare the launch of an offer that allows its customers to pay contactlessly by cell phone.
