Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas line, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to commit this event with glory and glory.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas line, which connects Russia and Germany directly under sea level on Tuesday on the Baltic Sea coast under orchestra sounding and at Finschmeckerbuffet.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his colleague Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically jointly turned the control of the valve that transports Russian gas into the western European network.
The new gas pipeline is expected to deliver 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year through a first pipeline of 1,224 km long which connects the St. Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of the total consumption of France - is expected to be completed at the end of 2012.
And you already let the eventuality of the construction of a third line sound on your own route.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building is a victory.
The project was very controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream pipeline will enable direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding any routes through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries lose a little of their power: for them it will now be more difficult to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, was not reluctant to compare the Nord Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin in order to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is extremely sensitive from a political point of view.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of a reduction in European energy, as the project has broken between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in enforcing its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, western countries that have high gas consumption and are slowing down their gas deposits.
“This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way,” said Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing to the extent to which the major gas contracts are also important from a political and economic side.
All this explains the broad smile of the Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply line.
The construction of this gas transmission line is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with concrete shell, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at about 200 meters deep.
In their construction, mine fields dating from the Second World War had to be evacuated.
“About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed for precautionary purposes,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
Furthermore, increased measures to protect fauna and flora had to be taken.
The line is a long metal line, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which has been interrupted by nothing over the entire length: neither valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers differed from it, as the Swedes were little eager to see a Russian state society permanently settling at the height of their coasts.
"In the event of a havarie, we will close the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller said.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas transmission pipe escapes to the air.
However, this case is considered by the designers to be only unlikely, since the silent seams were estimated to have a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
The state monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled from a seaship for external observation purposes, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, measuring a meter in diameter, is inserted into the interior of the pipeline and moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on possible deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to achieve this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF (each 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group of companies GDF Suez (each 9%).
These five companies have formed a corporate community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas line.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Gazprom has then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company on a renewable 20-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the quantity of real-life gas is," said Jens Müller.
The financing of the gas transmission construction was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should be 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are sure to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone carries the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline appears on a sandy coastline wooded with pine trees near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas exit gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other indicators of the incoming gas before it is transmitted to the German gas lines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with a million cubic meters of Russian gas per hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Started by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to add new style to writing.
It has a flair of adventure, hours spent in candlelight writing.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognizable, with its black, rectangular cover, rubber strap, egg-shaped sides, as it aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, headquartered in Milan, decided to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a specialist consultant for the company, is tasked with launching the new product on the market.
The notebook was inspired by an ancient production technique called Mole Skin, which denotes a cotton coat used, for example, for covering upholstery benches.
This type of notebook was in high demand among writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object that until the 20th century was considered an icon of avant-garde artists,” explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success comes.
Between 2006 and 2010 sales increased by 26% and established with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a phantom image of buyers, as the notebook excites business people as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultivated and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which initially had 12 employees, now employs more than 100 employees and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookstores, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in city centres and is committed to enforcing its identity.
“We followed the spirit of time and its new need for writing, which exists despite the boom of emails,” said Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: Recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour (Umweg)", in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a cover with leopard patterns on the occasion of the film festival in Locarno.
Moleskine benefited from his success and this cultural spirit of time and knew how to diversify his products: bags, schedules, fillers, computer covers... The brand has the entire range of items.
In autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today’s Syntegra Capital, opening up a new chapter in Moleskine’s history.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th Week of Work for Disabled".
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is always twice as high as the average: 19% versus 9% unemployment for the overall population.
Disheartening?
"No," emphasizes Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, which organizes the 'Week of Work for Disabled'.
“The progress made in fifteen years is considerable.”
“The unemployment rate was not twice as high then, but three times as high.”
“Notwithstanding, there is still so much to do.”
However, it must be said that for disabled unemployed people, many obstacles remain before they get a job.
It is more common for older people: 37% are older than 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have a high school and there are only 10,000 disabled among the 2.3 million students with higher education.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% among the disabled compared to 38% in total.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter work, and that form the "core of the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, a association founded in 1992, which helps companies to recruit disabled workers.
So much for the actual brakes.
The unspoken remains, the mental attitudes that are certainly developing, but still slowly developing.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entrepreneur for the journal La Cité stated that the surveyed managers have “a low level of knowledge regarding disabled persons” that is “over-represented” by “persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually underprivileged”.
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way ahead to achieve the employment target of 6% disabled employees, which was set out in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, dating from 2008, indicate a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now at about 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the organization that is tasked with collecting contributions from companies that violate this law.
The evidence: The number of "paying fees" at establishments has decreased as well as the sum of the amounts deposited between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which provides for tax increases, created a strong pressure on companies,” said Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also expresses real knowledge, especially in the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of the facilities between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
